The '''Bahengic''' (Pahungic) languages are a divergent branch of the [[Miao languages|Miao (Hmongic)]] languages. Speakers are among the ethnic ''Bunu'': Miao-speaking [[Yao people]] of China.
[[Pa-Hng language|Pa-Hng]] (Baheng) has long been recognized as a divergent language. Benedict (1986) argued that one of its dialects constituted a separate branch of the Miao–Yao family, and Ratliff (2010) found it to be the most divergent Hmongic language that she analyzed.<ref name="Ratliff2010">Ratliff, Martha. 2010. ''Hmong–Mien language history''. Canberra, Australia: Pacific Linguistics.</ref> Mao & Li (1997) determined that two poorly known languages are closely related to Pa-Hng, though none are mutually intelligible:<ref>毛宗武, 李云兵 / Mao Zongwu, Li Yunbing. 1997. 巴哼语研究 / Baheng yu yan jiu (A Study of Baheng [Pa-Hng]). Shanghai: 上海远东出版社 / Shanghai yuan dong chu ban she.</ref>
