{{Other uses|Black bear (disambiguation){{!}}Black bear}} {{Infobox settlement |official_name = Black Bear Ranch |other_name = |native_name = | |image_skyline = |imagesize = |image_caption = |image_flag = |flag_size = |image_seal = |seal_size = |image_shield = |shield_size = |image_blank_emblem = |blank_emblem_size = |pushpin_map = California |pushpin_label_position = right |pushpin_map_caption = Location map of Black Bear Ranch, United States |pushpin_mapsize = 200px |image_map = |mapsize = |map_caption = |image_map1 = |mapsize1 = |map_caption1 = |subdivision_type = Country |subdivision_name = United States |subdivision_type1 = State |subdivision_name1 = [[California]] |subdivision_type2 = Region |subdivision_name2 = [[Shasta Cascade]] |government_type = [[Land trust]] |leader_title = Founder |leader_name = Richard Marley |established_title = |established_date = 1968 |established_title2 = <!-- Incorporated (town) --> |established_date2 = |established_title3 = <!-- Incorporated (city) --> |established_date3 = |area_magnitude = 80 acre |area_total_km2 = |area_total_sq_mi = |area_land_km2 = |area_land_sq_mi = |area_water_km2 = |area_water_sq_mi = |area_water_percent = |area_urban_km2 = 0 |area_urban_sq_mi = 0 |area_metro_km2 = 0 |area_metro_sq_mi = 0 |population_as_of = 2013 |population_note = |settlement_type = [[Intentional community]] |population_total = 40 |population_density_km2 = |population_density_sq_mi = |population_metro = |population_density_metro_km2 = |population_density_metro_sq_mi = |population_urban = 0 |population_density_urban_km2 = 0 |population_density_urban_sq_mi = 0 |timezone = [[Pacific Time Zone]] |utc_offset = -8 |timezone_DST = [[Pacific Daylight Time]] |utc_offset_DST = -7 |coordinates = {{coord|41.24184|-123.17721|display=inline,title}} |elevation_ft = |postal_code_type = |postal_code = |area_code = |website = {{URL|http://www.blackbearranch.org}} }}
'''Black Bear Ranch''' is an 80-acre [[intentional community]] located in [[Siskiyou County]], California, about 25 miles from [[Forks of Salmon, CA|Forks of Salmon]]. It was founded in 1968,<ref name="miller">Timothy Miller, "The Historical Communal Roots of Ultraconservative Groups", in {{Citation |publisher = AltaMira Press |isbn = 978-0-7591-0204-0 |title = The Cultic Milieu |url = http://openlibrary.org/books/OL8007171M/The_Cultic_Milieu |author = Jeffrey Kaplan |publication-date = September 2002 |id = 075910204X }}</ref> with the slogan "free land for free people". It has been considered by some participants and commentators to be one of the more radical examples of communal living/intentional communities that grew out of the [[counterculture of the 1960s]].<ref name="Miles2008">{{cite book|author=Malcolm Miles|title=Urban utopias: the built and social architectures of alternative settlements|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GfRPfGzQx3kC&pg=PA84|accessdate=30 May 2011|year=2008|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-37575-7|pages=84}}</ref>
Before being converted into a commune, it was a [[ghost town]] that had been a gold mining settlement in the 1860s.<ref name="Sutton2005">{{cite book|author=Robert P. Sutton|title=Modern American communes: a dictionary|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pA01_CvpCsIC&pg=PA16|accessdate=30 May 2011|year=2005|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-32181-8|pages=16–17}}</ref> The commune's legal ownership<!--the land or the organization? there's a difference--> was held by one resident, Richard Marley,<ref name="trustdocument">Black Bear Ranch website, [http://blackbearranch.org/about/black-bear-family-trust-document/ Black Bear Family Trust Document]</ref> until in 1987 it was transferred to the Black Bear Family Trust,<ref name="miller" /> which limits development of the property and established trustees to oversee various specified duties. Black Bear Ranch was the subject of the 2005 documentary ''[[Commune (documentary)|Commune]]'' by Johnathan Berman. The commune still exists today and continues to follow the basic ideals which motivated its founding. At the Summer Solstice Gathering in 2013, there were over 40 residents, the highest population in decades. It is located in a steep pocket valley in the [[Siskiyou Mountains]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0439511/|title=Commune|author=|date=26 July 2005|publisher=|accessdate=8 April 2017|via=IMDb}}</ref>
== Early life ==
The motivation behind setting up the commune was to create an intentional community that would reflect the vision of the Beats and the Diggers of San Francisco.
According to the historian Timothy Miller, the community bought the property for $22,500 using money from a variety of sources including from supporters in the entertainment industry, as well as "one large unexpected angelic gift" and the "proceeds from a major [[LSD]] deal".<ref name="miller" /> The money from the entertainment industry was obtained through what [[Stephen Holden]] in ''[[The New York Times]]'' describes as "emotional blackmail", quoting Michael Tierra:
{{quote|You're making money off our lifestyle. It's time you gave back some to us.<ref name="nytimes">[https://movies.nytimes.com/2006/11/03/movies/03comm.html Just a Hardy Bunch of Settlers Who Left America and Moved to California], by Stephen Holden. ''The New York Times'', Nov. 3, 2006</ref>}}
Although they struggled at first due to a lack of planning,<ref name="terence">Malcolm Terence, [http://www.northcoastjournal.com/news/2008/07/10/return-black-bear/ Return to Black Bear], ''The Journal'', Humboldt County California.</ref> the community at Black Bear Ranch learned to live self-sufficiently, as the ranch was often snowed in for extended periods during the winter months, and was many hours' drive from the nearest city. The residents managed to gather large quantities of food and medical supplies to see them through the winter and were able to treat a variety of illnesses and medical problems onsite, delivering babies and performing veterinary care. The community [[homeschooling|homeschooled]] their children, and maintained tools like [[chainsaw]]s and cars without a need for mechanics. To raise money to pay for food and supplies, they found work fighting fires in the nearby forests.<ref name="miller" />
Members of the commune were key organizers of Ent Forestry, a co-operative which took tree planting and forest rehabilitation contracts with the US Forest Service and Redwoods National Park, and provided income to the commune for several years.
Despite their remoteness, the community managed to keep in contact with a variety of radical groups including the [[Hells Angels]] and [[Black Power]] groups.<ref name="Terence2000">{{cite book|author=Malcolm Terence|title=Free land, free love: tales of a wilderness commune|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zDTxAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=30 May 2011|date=January 2000|publisher=Black Bear Mining and Pub. Co.|isbn=978-0-9673242-0-3|pages=76}}</ref> There was a tension between those with a radical—even paramilitary—persuasion who wanted to pursue weapons training and possibly harbor radical political fugitives<ref name="BraunsteinDoyle2002">{{cite book|author1=Peter Braunstein|author2=Michael William Doyle|title=Imagine nation: the American counterculture of the 1960s and '70s|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R178zShWUtIC&pg=PA334|accessdate=30 May 2011|year=2002|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-93040-6|pages=334}}</ref> and the many pacifists. One of the founders of the commune, interviewed by the University of Kansas' 60s Commune Project and quoted in Miller:<ref name="miller" /> {{Quote|we had a whole bunch of dependent people there, helpless, half of them reading comic books all day, waiting for someone to light the fire, who would rouse themselves when they smelled something cooking. So we founded the Black Bear Get-With-It Party, and we wrote a credo and went and nailed it up like Martin Luther on the door of the main house. It said, "We came up here to take over the world, to take over our own lives, and as a first step, we're announcing that we're going to take over Black Bear Ranch." It caused great consternation. Our tactic was to get up at the first light, have a bowl of porridge, and get to work and work all day—unheard of, right? Never mind smoking dope, you know—get to work.}}
Miller also records how "a strong sense of community" including ritual peyote use led to a variety of social experiments being conducted including the abolishing of private property and also the institution of a rule to prevent "coupling," which banned anyone from sleeping with the same partner for more than two consecutive nights,<ref name="Sutton2005" /> although this had disastrous consequences after a [[venereal disease]] spread amongst the community. Despite the ban on coupling (considered "bourgoise decadence"),<ref name="nytimes" /> traditional feelings of resentment came back when they tried to work out who had slept with whom in order to treat the disease:<ref name="miller" /> {{quote|We made up a chart with who slept with who, just go down and put a little "X" on it, and it turned out that I think we had to treat everybody. But the funny thing was, people would look at the chart and say "Joe, you bastard, you cheated on me with that bitch?" And I remember coming up and going, "Look at that son of a bitch Michael, he screwed everybody! And look at me, I got no marks next to my name!}}
At one point, a group called the [[Shivalila]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=36074341|title=Gridley Lorimer Wright, IV (1934 - 1979) - Find A Grave Memorial|author=|date=|work=findagrave.com|accessdate=8 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/TheBookOfTheMother|title=The Book Of The Mother|first=|last=Shivalila|date=|publisher=|accessdate=8 April 2017|via=Internet Archive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theland.wikispaces.com/Black%20Mountain|title=TheLand - Black Mountain|author=|date=|work=wikispaces.com|accessdate=8 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/651/000207030/|title=Gridley Wright|author=|date=|work=nndb.com|accessdate=8 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://califias.blogspot.com/2014/10/gridley-wright-and-shivalila.html|title=Califia's Children: Gridley Wright and Shivalila|first=Michael|last=Marinacci|date=29 October 2014|work=califias.blogspot.com|accessdate=8 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nysun.com/arts/trying-to-remember-the-family-band/42868/|title=Trying To Remember the Family Band - The New York Sun|author=|date=|work=nysun.com|accessdate=8 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Shivalila.html?id=LlKgHAAACAAJ|title=Shivalila: Social Culture Based on LSD Research|first=Gridley Lorimer|last=Wright|date=1 January 1978|publisher=Children's Liberation Front|accessdate=8 April 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.justia.com/cases/california/court-of-appeal/2d/275/738.html|title=People v. Wright|author=|date=|work=justia.com|accessdate=8 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://casetext.com/case/people-v-wright-510|title=Casetext|author=|date=|work=casetext.com|accessdate=8 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lk8_ARNz-dYC&pg=PA662&lpg=PA662&dq=Wright|title=The Encyclopedia of Cults, Sects, and New Religions|first=James R.|last=Lewis|date=1 January 2002|publisher=Prometheus Books|accessdate=8 April 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/33652851/|title=Indiana Gazette from Indiana, Pennsylvania on August 19, 2006 &middot; Page 3|author=|date=|work=newspapers.com|accessdate=8 April 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://www.encyclopedia.com/religion/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/communal-after-1960 Communal – After 1960 - Encyclopedia.com] "Shivalila was founded in Bakersfield, California, in the 1970s by Gridley Lorimer Wright IV (1934-1979)."</ref> became part of the commune until they were asked to leave by the other members. ''The New York Sun'' describes them as a "nomadic cult of acid-taking, baby-worshiping hippies looking for the perfect place to bring up children"<ref name="nytimes" /> and they were led by a man called Gridley Wright.<ref>James Bowman, [http://www.nysun.com/arts/trying-to-remember-the-family-band/42868/ Trying To Remember the Family Band], New York Sun.</ref>
Very few rules were ever adopted by the community as Malcolm Terence notes: "Anarchists are good at lots of things but making rules isn’t one of them."<ref name="terence" /> After a hepatitis epidemic, they banned sitting on the kitchen counter, and they also banned turning the handle on the cream separator "because it used to drive people crazy when people would sit in the kitchen and play with the handle on the cream separator".<ref name="miller" />
== Life today ==
Life at the ranch continues on, with similar struggles about what communality means as took place during the early days. The rules have grown into a set of "Traditional Guidelines" which try to ensure "the continued existence of Black Bear Ranch and its tradition of communal living in a way that cares for and nourishes each other and the environment".<ref name="traditionalguidelines">Black Bear Ranch website, [http://blackbearranch.org/about/traditional-guidelines/ Traditional Guidelines]</ref> Decision making by the group is managed through weekly 'Circles'.
In April 2017, the ranch made news when 15-year-old student Elizabeth Thomas and her alleged kidnapper and former teacher Tad Cummins were found in a cabin in Cecilville, CA near the ranch after a month-long interstate manhunt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wkrn.com/2017/04/20/black-bear-ranch-details-on-commune-where-cummins-thomas-found/|title=Black Bear Ranch: Details on commune where Cummins, Thomas stayed|last=WKRN web staff|first=|date=2017-04-20|website=WKRN.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref> They had stayed for two weeks at Black Bear Ranch but were asked to leave, after which they moved into the cabin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wkrn.com/2017/04/20/nissan-rogue-used-by-tad-cummins-found-in-northern-california/|title=Tad Cummins arrested, Elizabeth Thomas rescued at California cabin|last=WKRN web staff|first=|date=2017-04-20|website=WKRN.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-04-21}}</ref>
