[[File:N°3 HAÏK alt version.jpg|thumb|right|Women wearing haik]] The '''haik''' ({{lang-ar|حايك}}) is a traditional women's garment worn in Algeria region.<ref>{{cite book|title=E.J. Brill's First Encyclopaedia of Islam 1913-1936|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xd5VonTOppMC&pg=PA220|year=1987|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-08265-4|page=220}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.library.cornell.edu/colldev/mideast/shroud.htm|title=THE SHROUD OVER ALGERIA: FEMICIDE, ISLAMISM AND THE HIJAB|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|accessdate=2016-08-09}} {{dead link|date=November 2017}}</ref> It is similar to the [[niqāb]], although it is usually white. It consists of a rectangular fabric covering the whole body,<ref>{{cite book|author1=Ambroise Queffélec|author2=Yacine Derradji|author3=Valéry Debov|author4=Dalila Smaali-Dekdouk|author5=Yasmina Cherrad-Benchefra|title=Le français en Algérie: Lexique et dynamique des langues|publisher=Duculot|place=Brussels|year=2002|page=343|isbn=2-8011-1294-1}}</ref> 6 meters by 2.2 meters in length, rolled up then held at the waist by a belt and then brought back to the shoulders to be fixed by [[fibula (brooch)|fibula]]e. It can be white or black.
== Etymology == The word is borrowed from the [[Maghrebi Arabic]] word ''hayk'', which comes from the Arabic verb ''haka'' which means "to weave". First used in French in the form ''Heque'' (1654), it underwent many variations{{snd}}''hayque'' (1667), ''alhaic'' (1670), ''eque'' (1670), ''haic'' (1683), ''hayc'' (1686). The word ''haik'' in French was at first of the feminine [[Grammatical gender|gender]] (1725) and became masculine in 1830.<ref>[[Alain Rey]], ''Dictionnaire historique de la langue française'', Le Robert, Paris, 1992 {{ISBN|2-85036-187-9}}.</ref>
== Origins == The haik is of Arab-Andalusian origin,<ref>{{cite web|title=Histoire du Hayek|url=http://www.daraziza.com/hayek/histoire.html|website=www.daraziza.com|accessdate=2017-11-04}}</ref> and present throughout the Maghreb.<ref name="Murray1838">{{cite book|author=Hugh Murray|title=The Encyclopædia of Geography: Comprising a Complete Description of the Earth, Physical, Statistical, Civil, and Political ...|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xpBPAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA15|year=1838|publisher=Carey, Lea and Blanchard|page=15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = El-Haik, une histoire à découvrir...au musée des arts populaires de Médéa|url = http://www.huffpostmaghreb.com/2015/06/29/el-haik-une-histoire-a-decouvrirau-musee-des-arts-populaires-de-medea_n_7687824.html|website = [[Huffington Post|Al Huffington Post]]|date=29 June 2015|accessdate = 2016-01-24}}</ref> In 1792, the ''m'laya'', a black veil, popular in the eastern part of Algeria, made its appearance to mourn [[Salah Bey ben Mostefa|Salah Bey]], Bey of [[Constantine, Algeria|Constantine]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=El Haïk, une étoffe symbole de pureté|url=http://dziriya.net/el-haik-une-etoffe-symbole-de-purete/|website=dziriya.net|date=|accessdate=2016-01-24}}</ref> Made from wool, silk or synthetic silk fabric, the haik succeeded, in a very short time, to spread throughout all regions of the country, but its use was adapted to the socio-cultural specificities of the region. One variety of the haik, the ''haik mrama'', became very popular among women for its design, the way it was worn, and the quality of the fabric used by artisans. The ''haik mrama'' appeared at the end of the nineteenth century and was worn by urban women of Algiers and its suburbs. This type of veil is often associated with feminine beauty and has inspired many [[Chaabi (music)|Chaabi]] poets and singers, who dedicated many of their works to them.{{cn|date=November 2017}}
A variation on the haik called the [[huik]] was worn from the 14th until the late 19th century in the Netherlands and Belgium, usually black and made of wool or silk. It was worn by women as a protection against bad weather. Later variants were worn during a period of mourning.
==Present-day use== *In [[Algeria]], women wear white haik on a daily basis (especially older women). *In [[Morocco]], the use of haik has disappeared, except in the cities of [[Chefchaouen]], [[Essaouira]] and [[Figuig]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Le français au Maroc: Lexique et contacts de langues|author1=Fouzia Benzakour|author2=Driss Gaadi|author3=Ambroise Queffélec|place=Brussels|publisher=Duculot|year=2000|isbn=2-8011-1260-7|page=213}}</ref> The color of the haik is black or blue in the cities of [[Taroudant]] and [[Tiznit]]. *In [[Tunisia]], the ''sefseri'', a Tunisian variant of haik made of a single piece of cloth that does not cover the face, has been virtually abandoned. However it is still sometimes traditionally worn,<ref name="Jousiffe2008">{{cite book|author=Ann Jousiffe|title=Tunisia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Boo4GQdE-bcC&pg=PA25|year=2008|publisher=New Holland Publishers|isbn=978-1-84537-864-6|page=25}}</ref> especially by older women.
